2. Column Description - Observations and Findings¶

Age :

  1. Mean and Median approximately match on the Age Criteria and hence there is not much skew in that Column.
  2. Standard Deviation is Huge, implying that age is spread out. Its correlation with other Quantities is of crucial importance.

Experience :

  1. We can see here that Age has -3 Years of Experience as its minimum, so its a bad anamoly in the data. That is not possible so we have to see the careful look.
  2. Experience has mean and median matched, so there is not much skew in the data.
  3. It has huge standard deviation too. That observation implies that the correlation with other Parameters need to be carefully observed.
  4. Experience of 43 years as a maximum seems to correspond to the maximum age of 67 years, but it should be dealt with proper suspicion because of the retirement age.

Income (in Dollars Per Year):

  1. Mean Income seems to be 73K and median is 64K, which is closer, but the maximum is more than double of the mean and also more than double of the 75 % indicating that there are some ridiculous outliers
  2. Standard deviation is riddiculously huge implying so much income inequality that we need to be careful with outliers. Can be analyzed using boxplot.

ZIP Code :

  1. This column has no relevance whatsoever regarding anything else.
  2. Correlation needs to be made with other Parameters.

Family :

  1. This is pretty Standard and seems to be Normally distributed and seems to have no unnatural outliers or anamolies.

CCAvg (in Dollars Per Month):

  1. Mean is close to Median implying no large skewing of the Data.
  2. Maximum value 10K is too high and way above 75% percentile viz., 2.5k. That implies that it has Outliers. Check for its significance in the boxplot and remove if possible.

Education :

  1. Minimum is 1, implying that all the Customers of the Bank are Undergraduates atleast. If there are any missing values, we can conclude otherwise later on.
  2. On an average the data tends more towards Advanced Graduate Level, with very low Standard deviation. That means most of the customers have good Education levels.

Mortgage (in Dollars):

  1. It seems to be Highly skewed data. The skew needs to observed because the mean is nowhere near the median and the maximum value is riddiculously high.
  2. Standard Deviation seems more like outlier than actual data. Boxplot or distplot needs to be done to make sure that there are very few outliers or a large number of outliers.

Personal Loan, Security Account, Online, CreditCard :

  1. Since these are Binary values there is nothing we can see, except take the count plot and see.

Eliminating Outliers¶

In [16]:
#Extreme Values of the Income are eliminated from the Data
Q1=df["Income"].quantile(0.25)
Q3=df["Income"].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
condition_for_outliers = (df["Income"] < (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)) | (df["Income"] > (Q3 + 1.5 * IQR))
#print(condition_for_outliers)
df=df.drop(df[condition_for_outliers].index)
df

def check_for_correlationratio(column,column2,correlation):
    if correlation[column][column2] > correlation_value: #You can change the value here with user input
        return (column1,column2)
    else:
        return  
def check_for_repetitions(columns_list):
    columns_list=list(filter(None,columns_list))
    for tuple_element1 in columns_list:
        for tuple_element2 in columns_list:
            if tuple_element1[0]==tuple_element2[1] and tuple_element2[1]==tuple_element1[0]:
                columns_list=columns_list.remove(tuple_element2)
    return columns_list

3. Distribution of the Target Columns¶

Both Securities account and CD Account are considered as liabilities of the Bank towards the customer. Hence, we need to separate them and contrast them against the Personal Loan criteria

Success ratio can be interpreted as the ratio of takers of the loan to the total customers of the bank. This should be maximized, keeping the budget minimum

Note : We can reload our original data because, since here the Income has got nothing to do with objectives asked for. But we continue with the same Dataframe with reduced/filtered dataframe.

#This Cell can be skipped completely. This is to show what happens in the background for Precision and Recall
TP_LR = df_Confusion_LR["Predict Yes"]["1"]
TN_LR = df_Confusion_LR["Predict No"]["0"]
Total_Yes=df_Confusion_LR["Predict Yes"].sum()
Total_No=df_Confusion_LR["Predict No"].sum()
FP_LR = Total_Yes-TP_LR
FN_LR = Total_No-TN_LR
print("True Positives (TP) : ", TP_LR)
print("\nTotal True Predictions :",Total_Yes )
print("\nTotal proportion True Positives that have been rightly predicted : ",TP_LR *100/Total_Yes, "%")
print("\nTrue Negatives (TN) : ", TN_LR)
print("\nTotal False Predictions :",df_Confusion_LR["Predict No"].sum())
print("\nTotal proportion False predictions that have been rightly predicted : ", TN_LR*100/Total_No, "%" )

print("\nType I Error",df_Confusion_LR["Predict Yes"]["0"])
print("\nType II Error",df_Confusion_LR["Predict No"]["1"])
Precision= TP_LR/(TP_LR+FP_LR)
print ("\nPrecision of the above Model is : ", Precision)
Recall = TP_LR/(TP_LR+FN_LR)
print("\nRecall of the above Model is : ",Recall)

7. Reasoning for a Data Model¶

Taking a careful look at the above scores, we can compare and decide that although all of the Models provide roughly the same amount of accuracy, there is a significantly different amount of Recall generated by them.

Based on that we can say that highest amount of Recall is generated by Naive Bayes Model, where as KNN generates the worst amount of Recall. Hence, we have to choose Naive Bayes as our Model for this Dataset.
